******
[3] Vegetable brassicas, eastern England
Date: Mon 16 Jan 2017
Source: HorticultureWeek [edited]
http://www.hortweek.com/alert-high-risk-leaf-spot-predicted-2017/edibles/article/1420948


ADAS [independent provider of agricultural and environmental consultancy, rural development services and policy advice] has warned that [light leaf spot] continues to be seen in East Anglia on cabbages and Brussels sprouts and is increasing in susceptible varieties.

ADAS has warned to be vigilant for signs on cauliflower, where the base of the petiole shows dirty black or pink-coloured lesions on trimmed heads. Light leaf spot was present in vegetable brassicas in Lincolnshire from October 2016

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[Light leaf spot (LLS) of _Brassica_ species is caused by the fungus _Pyrenopeziza brassicae_. In oilseed rape (_Brassica napus_), leaves become infected soon after sowing, but remain symptomless until lesions appear on older leaves. In severe cases, developing leaves and buds can be affected causing leaf distortion and stunting of plants. Stems may split and break off. Developing pods are often infected, leading to premature ripening of seed and pod shatter. Different vegetable brassicas vary in susceptibility to the fungus, but generally show spots and discolourations on leaves and stems which reduce quality and may also affect yield.

LLS is polycyclic and survives the summer on crop debris, volunteer oilseed rape and vegetable brassicas. Spores are spread by wind, rain splash and with infected plant material. Disease management may include varieties with decreased levels of susceptibility, removal of infected stubble, disease monitoring and timely fungicide applications.

In the UK, LLS has caused considerable yield losses of oilseed rape in the past estimated at GBP 40 million per year.

